  "text": "In turn, higher levels of perceived control should provide mothers with greater cognitive resources to cope with stressful parenting events and situations. In two studies, mothers' perceptions of control explained a significant portion of the variance in their stress levels [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Moreover, [CITATION_3] found that perceived control mediated the association between total support received from family and friends and parenting stress. Taken together, these findings suggest that support gained through interparental relationships decreases levels of felt stress because mothers feel more in control as parents.",
